User Interface Documentation

StratML Form

This point describes the main Strategic Markup Language Forms supported by this implementation.

In both forms (strategy and performance plans) the fields are grouped by the functional area in order to deal with the large amount of possible information.

Take into consideration that there are previous versions of the forms managed by the StratML community that can be also used. You can locate previous versions of the plans and MS Office plugins at stratml.org.

Introduction Step

The introduction steps shows the main available options:

- Create Strategic plan.

- Create a performance plan.

- Load or save an existing plan.

- Form configuration. URLs, etc.

StratML Performance Plan Form

The welcome screen of the performance plan form describes shortly the steps involved in the creation of the full plan, including performance information.

The performance information, intended for execution performance and evaluation purposes, is the main difference between a performance plan and an strategic plan.

Plan Information

The first step of the form handles the plan main information (name, identifier, description) and plan dates.

Submission information

The submission information step describes specific details about the plan document creation. This includes the publication dates, sources and the contact information of the document submitter.

There's also a field for additional information.

Organization page

The organization step holds the information about values, mission, vision and other high level information about the plan issuer organization.

- Values: Values describe remarkable principles or practices that the organization performs or define as desirable. They are not inputs or outputs directly involved in the analysis of the process, but management consider them as an achievement or desirable higher level output of the process.

- Mission: This is the main and definitive outcome expected from the main organization activity on the long term. As an opposition to Goals and Objectives this element is related to the main organization, while Goals and Objectives are usually related to the plan.

- Vision: This is a concept that describes how the organization interprets the organization activity in the actual context. It's a more descriptive than prescriptive concept.

Stakeholder Management

Stakeholders description dialog. Stakeholders can be described for several entities like Organizations, Goals and objectives.

Role Management

Common role management functionality.

Goals

The goals page manages plan specific goals information and the defined derived objectives.

It is important to remark the differences and relations between these two concepts. Goals are a more broader term and they are the main expected outcomes from the plan. They are not expected to be specified in detail. The goals are the expected results from the plan execution.

On the other side, objectives precise the specific scope of the goals. They are defined to measure and declare the actual expectations in the achievement of the goals.

Objectives are usually linked to a time frame, usually between three months and a year, while goals might span for several periods. Also, there might be different objectives related to different levels of achievement for a single goal in the same period.

It is important to point out some conceptual differences that can be even more subtle on other languages.

Performance

The performance page describes both the specific measure instances expectations and results.

This page is not used on strategic plans. They are used only on performance plans.

StratML Plan Form

This form describes the steps needed to create a Strategic Markup Plan.

An strategic plan differs from the full form in the fact that it lacks the performance information group, stakeholders and roles information.

Plan Revision

The Functionality include a plan revision step. The revision step offers the possibility to have a single view of the plan before the final submission.

The functionality, currently in development, will be a subset of the full plan report.

Configuration

These StratML forms are intended for integration in other systems. The integration success relies on the use of declarative technologies like XForms and a good amount of configuration capabilities.

The form based on XForms declarative technology and other open standards like W3C's Xhtml, Xslt, XPath, CSS, Svg, and ECMA's standards like Javascript.

The form should be configurable in two different ways. Functional specific configuration and also systems integration.

Plan configuration

The form can dynamically manage the base repo location and plan name. Using the configuration parameters, the form cam be used to copy plans, load them and store them in a different location.

Take into consideration that different browsers and browsers security configurations might impose limits to what URL's can be dynamically accessed from a website. Check your browser configuration if you need to work with documents on different servers or web applications.

Load Plan

The Load Plan dialog is designed for unexperienced users. Load a plan from a local directory or a remote server. The base path is taken from the configuration dialog but can be modified.

Take into consideration that different browsers and browsers security configurations might impose limits to what URL's can be dynamically accessed from a website. Check your browser configuration if you need to work with documents on different servers or web applications.

Languages Management

The form can dynamically change the language used.

If you are interested in adding support for another language please consider contributing to the StratML project.
